  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Commission negotiation is one of the most misunderstood aspects of selling a property. Most vendors know they can ask for a lower rate, and most agents expect to be asked. What is less understood is the relationship between commission rate, service level, and final sale price. Pushing commission down is straightforward. Working out what that costs you in the outcome is harder to see.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What agents typically charge in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, real estate commissions are not regulated and can vary significantly between agents and agencies. In Brisbane's inner east, rates for a residential sale typically sit somewhere between 2% and 3% of the sale price, plus GST. Some agents quote flat fees, particularly at lower price points. Others use tiered structures where a higher rate applies on any portion of the price achieved above an agreed threshold, which aligns the agent's incentive with achieving a strong result.</p>

      <p>The rate you are quoted will reflect the agency's pricing model, the agent's individual standing within their office, and how competitive they believe their market position is. Agents who are consistently achieving strong results in your suburb have less reason to discount because their track record justifies their rate. Agents who are newer to the area or working to build their portfolio may be more willing to move on price. This is worth keeping in mind when you are comparing proposals.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The maths most sellers miss</h2>
      <p>Commission is calculated on the sale price, so the number that matters most is the sale price itself. On a $1.2 million property, the difference between a 2.2% commission and a 2.5% commission is $3,600. That is a real number, but it needs to be weighed against what the agent's capability and effort are likely to produce in terms of sale price.</p>

      <p>A strong agent who achieves $1.22 million through skilled negotiation and a well-managed buyer competition will cost you more in commission than an agent who settles for $1.18 million at the first offer. The agent who produced the better result still puts more money in your pocket after their commission is paid. The question to ask is not whether you can reduce the commission rate. It is whether the agent you are engaging is the one most likely to maximise your sale price.</p>

      <p>When you are comparing two agents, do the maths on likely sale price differential rather than focusing on rate differential alone. If one agent has a track record of achieving prices 3-5% above comparable sales in your suburb and the other is quoting a rate that is 0.3% lower, the maths almost always favours the better-performing agent at the higher rate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When negotiating commission is reasonable</h2>
      <p>There are circumstances where asking for a different fee structure is entirely appropriate. If you are selling multiple properties at the same time, or if you own a property that is straightforward to sell in a hot market with limited competition, it is reasonable to have a conversation about the fee. If an agent is very motivated to win your listing and your property is in high demand, they may be willing to move.</p>

      <p>Tiered commission structures are worth asking about if they are not offered upfront. A structure where the agent receives a standard rate on the agreed reserve or asking price, and a higher rate on any amount achieved above that, creates a strong shared incentive. You pay more only if your agent earns you more, which is a sensible alignment of interests. Most reputable agents are willing to discuss this approach if you raise it.</p>

      <p>You can also ask about what is included in the commission versus what is billed separately. In Queensland, the marketing budget is typically separate from the commission. It is worth being clear upfront about what the commission covers and what the total cost of the campaign will be, including marketing and any additional costs, so you are comparing like with like when you are evaluating proposals.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What you risk by pushing too hard</h2>
      <p>There is a practical risk in negotiating aggressively on commission that is worth being honest about. Agents are human. When a vendor has pushed hard on rate, some agents will sub-consciously prioritise vendors who were easier to deal with when allocating their time and energy during a busy week. This is not ethical, but it is predictable human behaviour. An agent who is running five campaigns at once will spend more time on the campaign where the client relationship is strong.</p>

      <p>There is also the risk that an agent who has conceded significantly on commission will look to recoup that margin elsewhere, whether through reduced marketing quality, less active follow-up with buyers, or a lower threshold for recommending that you accept an offer rather than holding out for a better one. These things are hard to measure and easy to deny, but they are real risks in a commission-discounting dynamic.</p>

      <p>The more reliable way to ensure you are getting value is to select an agent whose track record in your specific market justifies their rate, negotiate a structure that aligns their incentives with your outcome, and hold them accountable through regular, specific vendor reporting throughout the campaign. That combination consistently produces better financial outcomes than choosing the lowest commission quote.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to approach the commission conversation</h2>
      <p>Rather than leading with "can you do better on the rate?", start by asking each agent to walk you through how they intend to run your campaign, what their comparable sale results look like in your suburb over the past twelve months, and how they handle buyer follow-up and negotiation. Once you have a clear picture of what you are getting for the fee, you are in a much better position to evaluate whether the rate represents value.</p>

      <p>If you genuinely believe the rate is too high relative to what is being offered, say so directly. A straightforward "I have spoken with two other agents and the fee is higher than I expected for this price range" is a reasonable thing to raise. A good agent will either justify their rate with specifics or offer an alternative structure. An agent who cannot explain their value clearly when asked is giving you useful information about how they will handle negotiations with buyers on your behalf.</p>

